aping Subjectivities." Finally, Part IV, "Oral Performance and Personal Power," considers the ways in which political authority and gendered resistance were established in early America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAcculturationzAmericaxHistoryvCongresses. 0aAcculturationzAmericaxHistoryxCongresses. 0aCulture conflictzAmericaxHistoryvCongresses. 0aCulture diffusionzAmericaxHistoryvCongresses. 0aCulture diffusionzAmericaxHistoryxCongresses. 0aIntercultural communicationzAmericaxHistoryvCongresses. 4aEarly American & Colonial History. 4aU.S. History.1 aSt. George, Robert Blair, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171786440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501717864423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501717864/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles